text_blocks.snippet: Extracranial arteries are blood vessels located outside the skull that supply blood to the head and neck. These include the common carotid arteries, internal carotid arteries, external carotid arteries, and vertebral arteries. They play a vital role in delivering oxygenated blood to the brain and other structures in the head and neck region.
snippet_highlighted_words: blood vessels located outside the skull that supply blood to the head and neck

list.title: Common Carotid Arteries (CCAs):
list.snippet: These are the main arteries in the neck that branch into the internal and external carotid arteries.

list.title: Internal Carotid Arteries (ICAs):
list.snippet: These arteries carry oxygenated blood directly to the brain.

list.title: External Carotid Arteries (ECAs):
list.snippet: These arteries supply blood to the face, scalp, and other structures in the head and neck, branching into various smaller arteries.

list.title: Vertebral Arteries:
list.snippet: These arteries run through the vertebrae in the neck and supply blood to the posterior part of the brain.

text_blocks.snippet: Extracranial arteries are crucial for maintaining proper blood flow to the brain, which is essential for brain function. Disruptions in the flow of these arteries can lead to various neurological problems, including stroke.
